Canada - Labour shortages identified in Toronto

A study funded by Human Resources Development Canada has found that growth in the Ontario city of Toronto will be halted unless gaps in the labour market are filled by the year 2010.

The study claims that by then, over 400,000 new jobs will need to be filled, which actually represents 13% of the entire labour market. The existing work force may need to be replaced by then, especially in skilled positions requiring a minimum qualification of at least a bachelor's degree.

The study recommends that the main solution to filling these gaps in the labour market would be immigration.

The government has been urged to support immigration programmes and efforts to integrate new migrants into the Canadian workforce. In light of this, the Toronto Region Immigrant Employment Council was created this month to improve access to certain areas of employment for immigrants in the Toronto area. The Council aims to bring together government, community organizations, employers, educators and other actors to improve access to employment for immigrants in the region so that they are able to use their skills, education, and experience more effectively.

Why apply now?

A common mistake is to apply for permanent residence when one needs it.  A better approach is to plan ahead and apply for it when you are ELIGIBLE.  Eligibility criteria are getting more stringent. 

Changes which can affect your eligibility 

-Changes in immigration policy 
-Changes in pass mark 
-Changes in assessment criteria 
-Changes in occupational demand 

You do not need to relocate immediately after your application for permanent residence is approved.  Normally, you can wait for 3 years from date of approval to relocate.  Furthermore, the application and approval process can take a long time, usually more than a year.  

We look forward to a meeting to discuss your needs. 

